    <h1>Plant Families</h1>
    <p><strong>Why do they matter?</strong></p>
    <p>Understanding plant families is crucial in permaculture design. Each family brings unique ecological, agricultural, and environmental benefits.</p>

    <!-- Plant Family List -->
    <div class="family">
        <h2>1. Fabaceae (Legume Family)</h2>
        <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Peas, beans, clover, alfalfa, pigeon pea, mimosa, acacia.</p>
        <p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Nitrogen fixation (improves soil fertility).</li>
            <li>Animal fodder.</li>
            <li>Ground cover (erosion control).</li>
            <li>Edible crops.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="family">
        <h2>2. Poaceae (Grass Family)</h2>
        <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Bamboo, sugarcane, lemongrass, vetiver, corn, wheat.</p>
        <p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Mulch and biomass production.</li>
            <li>Erosion control with deep roots.</li>
            <li>Animal fodder.</li>
            <li>Habitat for beneficial insects.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Add more families in the same format -->
    <div class="family">
        <h2>3. Asteraceae (Daisy Family)</h2>
        <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Sunflowers, dandelions, lettuces, artichokes, calendula.</p>
        <p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Dynamic accumulators (bring up nutrients).</li>
            <li>Pollinator attractors.</li>
            <li>Edible and medicinal uses.</li>
            <li>Ground cover and soil improvement.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

	<div class="family">
		<h2>4. Rosaceae (Rose Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Apples, pears, cherries, almonds, raspberries, roses.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits and nuts.</li>
			<li>Wildlife attractor (birds, insects).</li>
			<li>Shade provision.</li>
			<li>Aesthetic appeal.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>5. Lamiaceae (Mint Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Mint, basil, rosemary, lavender, oregano, thyme.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Pest repellents.</li>
			<li>Pollinator attractors.</li>
			<li>Medicinal and culinary herbs.</li>
			<li>Soil improvement through aromatic compounds.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>6. Brassicaceae (Mustard Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Cabbage, kale, mustard greens, radishes, turnips.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Fast-growing cover crops.</li>
			<li>Nutrient cycling.</li>
			<li>Edible greens and roots.</li>
			<li>Pest management (trap cropping).</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>7. Rutaceae (Citrus Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Oranges, lemons, limes, grapefruits.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits.</li>
			<li>Medicinal uses.</li>
			<li>Pollinator attractors.</li>
			<li>Companion planting for pest management.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>8. Apiaceae (Carrot Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Carrots, parsley, fennel, dill, coriander.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Pollinator attractors (umbel-shaped flowers).</li>
			<li>Edible roots, seeds, and leaves.</li>
			<li>Habitat for beneficial predatory insects.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>9. Amaranthaceae (Amaranth Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Amaranth, quinoa, beets, spinach.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible seeds and leaves.</li>
			<li>Drought tolerance for arid regions.</li>
			<li>Dynamic accumulators (nutrient cycling).</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>10. Myrtaceae (Myrtle Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Guava, eucalyptus, feijoa, cloves.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits.</li>
			<li>Aromatic oils for pest deterrence.</li>
			<li>Timber and firewood.</li>
			<li>Medicinal and antimicrobial properties.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>11. Solanaceae (Nightshade Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Tomatoes, potatoes, peppers, eggplants, ground cherries.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits and tubers.</li>
			<li>Nutrient-dense food crops.</li>
			<li>Intercrop to deter pests when paired with other families.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>12. Cucurbitaceae (Gourd Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Pumpkins, squash, cucumbers, melons, gourds.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits.</li>
			<li>Ground cover for weed suppression.</li>
			<li>Biomass production.</li>
			<li>Shade for soil and companion plants.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>13. Moraceae (Fig Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Figs, mulberries, breadfruit, jackfruit.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>21
			<li>Edible fruits.</li>
			<li>Shade trees for understory plants.</li>
			<li>Animal fodder (leaves and fruits).</li>
			<li>Habitat for wildlife.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>14. Euphorbiaceae (Spurge Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Cassava, castor oil plant, poinsettia.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible tubers (cassava).</li>
			<li>Biofuel and oil production.</li>
			<li>Drought tolerance for arid climates.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>15. Malvaceae (Mallow Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Okra, hibiscus, cotton, cacao, linden trees.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible and medicinal crops.</li>
			<li>Fiber production (cotton).</li>
			<li>Shade and habitat trees.</li>
			<li>Pollinator attractors.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>16. Zingiberaceae (Ginger Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Ginger, turmeric, cardamom.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Medicinal and culinary spices.</li>
			<li>Soil health improvement.</li>
			<li>Companion planting for pest deterrence.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>17. Anacardiaceae (Cashew or Mango Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Mangoes, cashews, pistachios, poison ivy.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits and nuts.</li>
			<li>Wildlife attractor.</li>
			<li>Shade and windbreak trees.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>18. Lauraceae (Laurel Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Avocado, cinnamon, bay leaves.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits and spices.</li>
			<li>Pollinator and wildlife attractors.</li>
			<li>Shade trees for diverse systems.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>19. Polygonaceae (Buckwheat Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Buckwheat, rhubarb, sorrel.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Fast-growing cover crops.</li>
			<li>Dynamic accumulators.</li>
			<li>Edible leaves and seeds.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>20. Pinaceae (Pine Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Pines, firs, spruces, cedars.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Timber and firewood.</li>
			<li>Windbreaks and erosion control.</li>
			<li>Resin and other useful by-products.</li>
			<li>Habitat for wildlife.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>21. Araceae (Aroid Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Taro, elephant ear, philodendrons.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible tubers (taro).</li>
			<li>Tropical shade plants.</li>
			<li>Ornamental and aesthetic uses.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>22. Palmae/Arecaceae (Palm Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Coconut, date palm, oil palm, sago palm.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible fruits and oils.</li>
			<li>Biomass production.</li>
			<li>Shelter and materials (e.g., thatching).</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>23. Moringaceae (Drumstick Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Moringa (Drumstick tree).</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Highly nutritious leaves, seeds, and pods.</li>
			<li>Drought tolerance.</li>
			<li>Animal fodder and biomass.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="family">
		<h2>24. Betulaceae (Birch Family)</h2>
		<p><strong>Examples:</strong> Birch, hazelnut, alder.</p>
		<p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
		<ul>
			<li>Edible nuts.</li>
			<li>Nitrogen fixation (alder species).</li>
			<li>Timber and firewood.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	

    <div class="family">
        <h2>25. Proteaceae (Protea Family)</h2>
        <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Macadamia nuts, banksia.</p>
        <p><strong>Roles:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Edible nuts.</li>
            <li>Wildlife attractor.</li>
            <li>Adaptation to nutrient-poor soils.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
